Former First Lady Barbara Bush, wife of 41st President George H. W. Bush, passed away at the age of 92. Mrs. Bush served as a trusted advisor to her husband and was known for her advocacy for literacy. She attended over 500 events related to literacy during her husband's time as Vice President. Mrs. Bush's legacy extends beyond her role as a political figure, as she was remembered for her warmth and friendship. She was also seen as a symbol for women's empowerment and embraced accessibility as a First Lady. The Bush family and public officials paid tribute to her, highlighting her impact as a mother, wife, and First Lady. First Lady Melania Trump will attend Mrs. Bush's funeral, and President Trump has ordered flags to fly at half-staff in her honor.